    "ADU1": {
      "text": "The primary fault line in the analytic philosophy of action is the debate between causal/Davidsonian and interpretivist/Anscombian theories of action.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "The fundamental problem of the former is distinguishing intentional from non-intentional causal chains; the fundamental problem of the latter is producing an account of the relation between an agent acting because she had a reason.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "It is argued that Hegel's conception can be used to develop the causal and interpretivist position by solving both theory's fundamental problems.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "Anscombe claims that 'The primitive sign of wanting is trying to,' which suggests a teleological criterion of striving or trying as intentional attitudes.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "Hegel clearly understands agency in teleological terms.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "If a teleological account can be given of this production via animation by reasons, then it should respond to the challenge to provide a positive account of the relation underlying the 'because' in reasons explanation.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "Hegel's version of this claim is phrased in terms of a conception of self-determination as 'elasticity' as opposed to the passivity involved in causal interaction.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "The reciprocal interaction of end and behavior in trying makes the end an existent and immanent organizing principle in a way that laws are not, on Hegel's view.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "Hegel holds that teleology promises a better articulation of the individuality of its relata than mechanism does.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "Teleological production is therefore clearly intended by Hegel to be a replacement for the notion of a self-cause that has played such an important role in understandings of agency.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "The systematic orientation of the system itself changes through its realizations of the goal (and the frustration of attempts at realization).",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "To realize our ends, we use our bodies as means in mechanical relations to other objects.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "This action on the world has a reaction on us and changes us, and in turn modifies our ends.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "Hegel's view has important advantages over Rowland Stout's contemporary teleological view of agency.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "Hegel's avoidance of the first result is just his inclusion of plasticity and persistence in the nature of a teleological process.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "The diversity and meaningfulness that Anscombe so powerfully makes central to the understanding and explanation of action are organized by a substantial articulation of the force of the 'because' in action explanations by reasons or intentions.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
