{
  "ADUs": {
    "1": {
      "text": "The primary fault line in the analytic philosophy of action separates those that advocate a causal relation between intention and action—a position most often traced to Donald Davidson—and those that deny causality in favor of what is often phrased as an 'interpretive' relation between the two—a position most often traced to Elizabeth Anscombe.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "2": {
      "text": "The fundamental problem of the former is producing criterion for distinguishing intentional from non-intentional causal chains; the fundamental problem of the latter is producing an account of the relation between agent and reason in 'she acted because she had the reason.'",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "3": {
      "text": "Goal-directed behavior is identified instead by the pattern of the activity's responsiveness to the goal and the resources for its achievement in the environment.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "4": {
      "text": "The means is therefore Hegel's way of talking about trying as objective and substantial.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "5": {
      "text": "The plasticity is a way of talking about the way in which the purpose illuminates the context and presents processes as means; this is the cunning of reason.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "6": {
      "text": "The criterion for distinguishing deviant from standard intentional chains is the systematic orientation of the agents intentional stance, including those causal chains that are not directly productive of the action.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
